{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d39485b-b5cf-4b1d-b96f-ed1b2d9d38f7","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level methods are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. The simplest migration path:\n\n**Option 1 — Subscribe to Window events in `CreateWindow`:**\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Subclass `Window` and override methods:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` / `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed` |\n\nFor platform-specific lifecycle hooks, you can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2490417b-fa93-49c5-acbb-d024e0d27e1a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to window events.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, you can handle app lifecycle through window events by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribing to events like `Created`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying` on the `Window` object. Alternatively, you can create a custom `Window` subclass and override methods like `OnCreated`, `OnStopped`, and `OnResumed`. The `Application` class itself no longer exposes those virtual lifecycle methods that existed in Xamarin.Forms, so the pattern has shifted entirely to the window level.","outputTokens":871,"requestId":"4830:348511:77861DB:83D30C1:69F3FB8E"},"id":"e36796fb-6948-4da4-9372-30e56704e457","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:02:22.426Z","parentId":"9a5b207f-9d5d-4456-aae3-44b32ed77294"}
